HEADWORD: Hut
<hw>Hut</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hotte</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>hut</ets>, G. <ets>h⟦uum⟧tte</ets>, OHG.
<ets>hutta</ets>, Dan. <ets>hytte</ets>, Sw. <ets>hydda</ets>; and F.
<ets>hutte</ets>, of G. origin; all akin to E. <ets>hide</ets> to
conceal. See <er>Hude</er> to conceal.]</ety> <def>A small house, hovel,
or cabin; a mean lodge or dwelling; a slightly built or temporary
structure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death comes on with equal footsteps⟦br⟧
To the hall and <qex>hut</qex></q>. <rj><qau>Bp. Coxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hutch</ent>⟦br⟧
